poland will suspend plans to build its 
second nuclear power plant because of the doubts and fears 
expressed by society state radio said 
according to the report industry minister mieczyslaw wilczek 
met with provincial governors from western poland whose provinces 
are near the klempicz plant and told them he favored a 
comprehensive review of the development program of the nuclear 
power industry in poland 
wilczek told the governors of the pila poznan and gorzow 
wielkopolska provinces that decisions about the fate of the 
project will be made on the basis of a comprehensive and thorough 
analysis of the fuelenergy situation up to the year 2000 the 
report said 
the state news agency pap early today said it had no word about 
such a decision 
the plans to construct the nuclear plant in the pila province 
town of klempicz has aroused protests in western poland the plant 
to be finished by the year 2000 would be about 30 miles north of 
poznan a city of 585000 people 110 miles from the east german 
border 
marches protesting the plant have become frequent events since 
the plans to build were announced in 1987 kemplicz would be the 
second polish nuclear plant after one in zarnowiec on the baltic 
coast where construction has begun that plant is scheduled to 
begin producing power in 1991 
the plants are based on soviet designs concerns about possible 
nuclear accidents have become much more acute among poles since the 
1986 accident at chernobyl in the soviet ukraine which borders 
poland 
