<TEXT>
farmers are getting more for their grain 
livestock and other commodities than they did last year but their 
net income is expected to drop from last years record according 
to the agricuture department 
prices measured by a usda index dropped 2 percent from march to 
april but were still 12 percent higher than a year ago the 
departments agricultural statistics board said friday in its 
preliminary report 
lower prices for cattle eggs hogs soybeans and lettuce were 
mostly responsible for the decrease from the march average while 
higher prices for tomatoes oranges and potatoes offset part of the 
decline for the other commodities 
new quarterly figures showed prices paid by farmers to meet 
expenses were up 11 percent from january and averaged 54 percent 
more than in april 1988 
higher prices for fuels fertilizers seeds autos and trucks 
tractors and other machinery contibuted most to the increase in the 
index since january the report said lower prices for feed 
and feeder cattle and calves were partially offsetting 
and department economists say net cash income of farmers is 
expected to fall 12 percent to 16 percent this year to a range of 
48 billion to 52 billion from the record 1988 level of 58 
billion 
net cash income is the amount farmers have at their disposal 
during the year and represents the difference between gross cash 
income and cash expenses cash income rose last year despite the 
drought partly because of higher market prices and crops farmers 
had stored from previous harvests 
the decline this year is expected to stem from farmers larger 
cash expenses as they boost plantings and also because of lower 
federal subsidies 
consumer food prices are still forecast by usda to rise an 
average of 3 percent to 5 percent this year following a 41 
percent increase in 1988 however department economists say it is 
likely that the 1989 forecast will be revised upward depending on 
how current conditions shape up 
in another report the department said the soviet union has 
bought an additional 105 million metric tons of us corn for 
delivery this year under a longterm supply agreement 
officials said the latest corn sales by unidentified private 
exporters pushed the total grain bought by the soviets this year to 
almost 183 million tons close to the record 186 million tons 
moscow purchased from the united states in 198485 corn makes up 
about 143 million tons and wheat 4 million 
the corn is scheduled for delivery by sept 30 the end of the 
sixth year of a longterm grain supply agreement between the soviet 
union and the united states 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 105 million tons 
of corn would be about 41 million bushels 
corn prices have been averaging about 253 per bushel at the 
farm level according to the latest usda fiveday average meaning 
that the latest sale could have a farm value of more than 100 
million 
