west german officials say nato nations 
are starting to line up against the us and british views in a 
major disarmament dispute within the western alliance 
chancellor helmut kohls call for superpower negotiations on 
shortrange nuclear weapons has placed him in a battle of wills 
against both president bush and british prime minister margaret 
thatcher 
mrs thatcher and kohl are scheduled to meet sunday in west 
germany to discuss the issue 
foreign minister hansdietrich genscher spent part of friday 
talking about the dispute one of the most divisive in recent years 
in the north atlantic treaty organization with us ambassador 
vernon a walters 
a foreign ministry statement said both sides expressed their 
belief that the alliance will jointly resolve the stillopen 
question of a formulation of a comprehensive disarmament 
concept 
but there were no indications that would happen soon 
genschers spokesman said seven of the 16 nato members 
including west germany support kohl 
west germany wants the united states to agree to talks with the 
soviet union on the shortrange weapons and notes that nato decided 
in favor of such negotiations in 1987 
most of natos shortrange nuclear weapons are based in west 
germany and would be used exclusively on german soil in the event 
of war 
washington rejects the west german insistence on negotiations 
saying talks on tactical nuclear arsenals should not begin as long 
as the warsaw pact alliance has a superiority in conventional 
forces 
west german polls show that the electorate favors such talks 
the military reductions announced by mikhail s gorbachev has made 
the soviet leader a popular figure in western europe 
the dispute has led to lobbying efforts by both sides among the 
nato members 
genscher told parliament on friday we can see that we are 
finding more and more understanding for this position for 
negotiations within the whole alliance 
