honors had come while he was alive 
flipper was born into slavery in thomasville he moved with his 
family and its owners to atlanta and after the civil war attended 
atlanta university before winning nomination to west point 
flipper was graduated from the academy in 1877 commanded an 
allblack cavalry regiment in oklahoma and then was put in charge 
of the fort sill commissary in 1881 he was charged with 
embezzling 3791 and with conduct unbecoming an officer 
at a courtmartial maccoll said was plagued with racism and 
irregularities flipper was acquitted of theft but convicted of 
unbecoming conduct 
after flipper was exonerated in 1977 west point dedicated a 
bust of him at the academy and named a portion of the library in 
his honor the academy also established an annual award in his name 
for the cadet who has survived the greatest hardship 
in 1978 flippers body was removed from an unmarked grave in 
atlanta where he died in 1940 at the age of 84 and was reburied 
near his parents graves in thomasville with full military honors 
