<TEXT>
the hot line the link set up 
between washington and moscow more than 25 years ago to reduce the 
risk of an accidental war has fallen into foreign hands 
the hot line was part of a division western union corp sold 
last week to swissowned telecolumbus usa of new york for 56 
million as part of a reorganization western union said 
in a deal approved by the federal communications commission 
telecolumbus acquired the privateline service of itt world 
communications a company acquired 16 months ago by western union 
western union which is based in this northern new jersey city 
kept the divisions telex and international cablegram businesses 
telecolumbus is owned by motorcolumbus ag a 
telecommunications and cable television company based in baden 
switzerland western union spokesman warren bechtel said saturday 
the line which consists of satellite connections and ground 
lines is secure because messages are encoded as they travel 
between the united states and the soviet union navy lt cmdr 
james cudla a navy spokesman was quoted as saying in saturday 
editions of the starledger of newark 
contrary to popular belief the hot line is not a red phone 
sitting on the presidents desk pentagon spokeswoman jan bodanyi 
said saturday 
hotline messages are transmitted from a small room in the 
pentagon housing computer terminals they instantly appear on 
soviet screens and can be printed out at the rate of 1800 words a 
minute five years ago the ability to send facsimiles was added 
voice conversations are considered more likely to be 
misunderstood or mistranslated ms bodanyi said 
itt corp set up the hot line in 1963 after president kennedy 
expressed concern after the cuban missile crisis about the amount 
of time it took to contact soviet leaders 
us and soviet officials send test messages in their own 
languages alternating each hour to make sure the line operates 
the tests are culled from literature and encyclopedias 
the sale drew criticism from rep matthew rinaldo of new jersey 
the ranking republican on the house telecommunications subcommittee 
rinaldo said he was concerned that the link which could make 
the difference between war and peace is controlled by a third 
party he said he would call for a hearing on the issue 
its time we began taking a hard look at how foreign ownership 
of vital services affects our national security rinaldo said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

