<TEXT>
the eyes of many investment managers inflation 
worriers and economic forecasters are watching still another 
statistic just as theyve been doing every day for several weeks 
they are scrutinizing digits percentages and even decimal 
points of the latest monthly business activity report from the 
national association of purchasing management seeking in it signs 
about the immediate future 
last week it was the report on consumer spending aftertax 
income and the savings rate later this week the microscope will be 
turned on newhome sales factory inventories nonfarm payrolls 
consumer debt and similar reports 
all this activity creates great excitement ranging from terror 
to elation pontificators orate portfolio managers change 
investments learned academics comment sagely the white house 
often has something to say as well 
but when all is said and done the question remains do the 
statistics of one month or one week mean very much if anything 
probably not and the reasons are obvious and numerous 
to begin with there are seasonal and other aberrations that 
cause shortterm reports to deviate from the longerterm trend as 
more information comes in revisions and adjustments often follow 
and corrections too 
it is not at all uncommon either for one months statistics to 
signify something entirely different from the month before or the 
one that follows moreover opinions of the same statistics vary 
from month to month 
it is for reasons such as these that wise users of statistics 
wait for confirmation which doesnt occur until statistics for a 
couple of months at least show the same configuration or until 
related data offer support 
knowledge of this doesnt of course deter anyone in an 
economic world in which insight into the future can be turned into 
megadollars an entire industry exists on grabbing and analyzing 
any numbers that float by 
among them are stock market analysts academics with or seeking 
a popular following investors the media economists seeking to 
prove that their theses are correct and worry warts of various 
stripes and spots 
worriers and those who feed them proliferate in an economy 
that is seen these days as being on the edge of a precipice any 
piece of statistical dust thus can be the weight that tips the 
precarious balance 
however in a field of economics in which the most basic of 
premises may be incorrect how can a speck of dust be that 
important if doubts exist about the causes of inflation for 
example can one months statistics be that important 
at the moment one of the most widely held theories about the 
current economy is that the budget deficits and federal debt are 
likely to cause a catastrophe it is probably the least 
controversial of all current economic issues 
however some of the sharpest brains in american economics 
disagree 
prof robert heilbroner and peter bernstein authors of the 
debt and the deficit state the national debt will not as is 
widely thought impoverish our grandchildren that only a small 
percentage of it is owed to foreigners and that the national debt 
and deficit are not large by historic standards 
they are not alone prof robert eisner of harvard former 
president of the american economic association contends that the 
true deficit is much smaller than thought and that everyone would 
know it with proper accounting methods 
if such an enormous disagreement exists about such a fundamental 
concept of american life why should one vagrant grain of 
statistical dust have an important and even enormous impact on the 
present and future 
it is something to think about this week when you read the 
reports about construction spending and installment credit and 
factory inventories and nonfarm payrolls 
</TEXT>
